<TEXT>
the presidents of latin americas three biggest debtor nations 
all hailed president bushs proposal to forgive billions of dollars 
of latin american countries foreign debt 
bushs plan to forgive part of the 12 billion owed by latin 
american and caribbean nations to the us government was welcomed 
too by the head of the biggest american creditor bank 
latin american leaders also praised bushs announcement 
wednesday that the united states would work with western european 
nations and japan to channel up to 300 million annually to latin 
america to spur foreign investment 
bush urged that work begin on a hemispherewide free trade 
zone but this was received more cautiously by some latin 
american governments 
latin american experts noted that bushs proposal affects only a 
small part of latin americas total foreign debt of more than 400 
billion 
brazilian president fernando collor de mello told bush in a 
telephone call that his proposal was comprehensive bold and 
innovative brazils foreign debt of 114 billion is the biggest 
among developing nations 
a spokesman for mexican president carlos salinas de gortari 
the third worlds secondbiggest debtor at 93 billion said 
salinas considered bushs speech a very important redefinition of 
the us position regarding economic development in latin america 
president carlos saul menem of argentina said he was 
satisfied with bushs speech argentinas foreign debt of 66 
billion ranks third in latin america 
menems spokesman humberto toledo said bushs statements showed 
that the united states was not going to overlook the problems of 
latin america because of changes in eastern europe where formerly 
communist nations also are seeking aid from the west 
however argentine economy minister antonio erman gonzalez said 
bushs plan for a hemispherewide common market is not for the 
immediate future it is a look at the medium and longterm 
john reed president of citicorp a large us commercial bank 
that has 8 billion in loans to latin america said he welcomed 
bushs initiative as a way to bring economic growth and prosperity 
to the region 
reed said bushs proposal would meet the objections of 
commercial banks to the us governments third world debt plan 
outlined last year by treasury secretary nicholas brady 
bradys plan offered incentives for commercial banks to write 
off some of their 13 trillion in third world debt but did not 
address the debt owed to the governments of the united states and 
other industrial nations 
commercial banks had argued they were being forced to shoulder 
the entire burden of debt reduction 
american officials said smaller countries such as honduras el 
salvador and jamaica would benefit the most from bushs debt 
forgiveness plan because a higher percentage of their foreign debt 
was to the us government 
honduran president rafael callejas called bushs announcement 
encouraging news 
officials said the united states would propose substantial 
writeoffs in the 7 billion in aid loans that us government 
agencies have made at belowmarket interest rates to the most 
heavily burdened countries 
the amount of debt forgiveness would depend on each countrys 
willingness to undertake economic reforms under the supervision of 
the international monetary fund 
the officials said the united states will also sell a portion of 
its 5 billion in marketrate loans to help facilitate 
debtforequity and debtfornature swaps 
bush said some of the us government debt could be swapped to 
set aside environmentally endangered land 
