<TEXT>
the two german states on sunday take their 
biggest step toward ending the four decades of division imposed 
after world war ii once again sharing a common currency and 
economy 
they will also share uncertainty over everything from a united 
germanys military role to their new nations name east germans 
worry about their jobs west germans wonder if their eastern 
cousins remember how to work 
many germans are still stunned by the pace of change since the 
ouster of east german communist leader erich honecker last october 
his downfall ended 40 years of ironfisted stalinist rule that 
followed the war 
merging the two nations without skipping too many beats in west 
germanys mighty economic rhythm is going to be difficult 
even theo waigel the passionately prounification finance 
minister in bonn has acknowledged that germany is embarking on an 
economic adventure 
in one stroke sunday most east germans will get thousands of 
dollars worth of west german marks which will become the common 
currency for both sides 
the west german mark will replace the virtually worthless east 
german currency and staterun businesses in east germany will be 
forced to compete for customers to survive 
there are countless scenarios of what might happen between 
sunday and early december when bonn hopes to see full unification 
completed 
depending on who is talking unemployment in east germany could 
hit several hundred thousand 4 million or almost anywhere in 
between 
unrest and disturbances are possible some experts say as east 
germans come back from their newly affordable summer vactions in 
venice mallorca and elsewhere to find they have no jobs 
others see inflation topping 10 percent or nearly three times 
its current pace 
in berlin and at other points along the rapidly disappearing 
border between east and west germans are eager to talk about their 
concerns 
basically we are happy says wilfriede dybowski of east 
berlin but we dont know whats going to happen to our jobs or 
whether we can face up to the new competition were pretty 
worried 
ms dybowski works for deutsche schallplatten gmbh a company 
that makes and assembles compact discs and records like thousands 
of east german businesses it must get rid of the countrys own 
products to make way for western goods 
we also have to cut the number of workers to the minimum 
possible said the smiling 55yearold ms dybowski we hope 
to stay in business 
just 100 yards away from ms dybowski on the western side of the 
berlin wall an elderly west berlin man gave a gloomy assessment 
the east germans have forgotten how to work said hubert 
enzenross 70 and my pension wont be going up that much all 
the money has to go over there to the east 
enzenross added its good that communism has fallen as for 
the rest its just not clear 
the berlin native stood in the shadow of the reichstag the 
imposing historyladen parliament building that could one day 
become the seat of the new countrys legislature 
the euphoria over the crumbling of the berlin wall last fall has 
been replaced by a sober realization that unification will cause 
discomfort in the short term 
still virtually everyone agrees the bold experiment will pay 
off in the long run 
we are hammering berlin back together has become the citys 
motto 
that saying is both figurative and literal as work crews rejoin 
pipes wires subway lines and other vital links hacked asunder in 
1961 
along the borders between the two countries the once 
impenetrable communist fences and walls are being hauled into the 
scrapheap of history as quickly as crews can work 
pedestrians and passenger cars at many points cross freely back 
and forth as bored east german guards stroll around or listen to 
the latest western rock music on the radio 
thousands of details remain to be worked out in the coming 
months ranging from placating soviet objections to nato membership 
for the joined country to meshing the two legal systems 
west berlin mayor walter momper infuriated many by proposing 
that west germany adopt some east german laws specifically a 
highway speed limit and a ban on drinking and driving 
it is uncertain what the new nation with nearly 80 million 
people will be called 
some have objected to the single name deutschland or 
germany saying it would call to mind too many memories of the 
samenamed country that unleashed nazi terror on europe 
</TEXT>
