<TEXT>
soldiers clad in black tshirts 
reading we kill for peace lounge near a buddhist temple 
smoking cigarettes and cracking jokes their automatic weapons lean 
against a nearby wall 
shops and offices on the towns narrow main street are boarded 
up and deserted a sole army jeeps speeds along the road 
welcome to vavuniya one of hundreds of cities left ghost towns 
by a 7yearold civil war 
more than 450000 people have fled the countrys northern and 
eastern sectors since a resurgence of fighting june 11 between 
militant tamil separatists and government troops 
at least 1679 combatants have been killed since the fighting 
broke out including civilians killed during government raids on 
rebel hideouts the government acknowledged it killed civilians 
during such raids this week on the city of jaffna 
vavuniya 135 miles northeast of colombo is the first northern 
settlement on the road to the jaffna peninsula a stronghold of 
tamil rebels fighting for an independent homeland 
rebels seized vavuniya shortly after they began overrunning 
police stations and attacking military camps june 11 
government troops counterattacked five days later recapturing 
the town after a battle in which nine soldiers and at least 67 
rebels were reported killed twelve civilians also died in the 
fighting 
since then the town which once had 18000 residents has 
emptied most people have gone to distant villages to live with 
relatives 
we cleared the town of people and have sealed off the three 
main entrances after recapturing the area said brig sathis 
jayasuriya army chief in vavuniya 
but the rebels are still capable of laying ambushes on the 
outskirts of the town he added 
the fight for vavuniya is typical of combat ravaging hundreds of 
villages which has left hundreds of thousands of people homeless 
after taking vavuniya tamil rebels built sandbagged bunkers on 
the streets and painted colorful pictures of dead comrades on 
building walls 
now vavuniya is occupied by government troops who man posts at 
three strategic junctions at one a government soldier draped a 
belt of machinegun bullets around his neck 
we have to be extremely careful since it is easy for the 
rebels to gain access to the town and attack civilian targets 
with bombs the soldier said 
on tuesday rebels ambushed and killed five soldiers on a road 
clearing operation at madukanda village north of vavuniya 
we have learned from our past mistakes and are now capable of 
destroying the rebels said a young colonel parami kulatunga 
tamils make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people the 
rebels claim they are discriminated against by the majority 
sinhalese who comprise 75 percent of the population 
in vavuniya long considered rebel country nearly 80 percent of 
the population was tamil the rest were sinhalese and moslem 
the tamil tigers have to be destroyed said kirith 
seneviratne a sinhalese clerk who fled vavuniya for a refugee 
camp both communities have lived together for so many years but 
now it is a case of finishing them off 
</TEXT>
