<DOCNO> AP900629-0021 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
what was a national embarrasment three 
centuries ago a warship that sank 15 minutes into its maiden 
voyage is now prominently displayed in a new museum 
the dockside museum opened this month to display the vasa which 
capsized in stockholm harbor in 1628 killing about 50 of the 
dignitaries and sailors on board 
the 200footlong warship bore the family name of king gustavus 
ii adolphus who had ordered it built to support his military 
campaigns in eastern europe 
nobody dared tell gustavus eager to get the vessel into action 
that it was dangerously unsteady a test involving 30 men running 
from side to side across the vasas deck was halted when it 
appeared that one more run would tip her over 
it took only a puff of wind to capsize the vasa barely a mile 
from where it was launched it sank in 110 feet of water and 
remained there until 1961 when it was raised and placed in an 
aluminum shed 
now in the 35 million museum tourists can use computer 
simulations to try to make the vasa seaworthy 
using computer screens museumgoers can add ballast remove 
guns and change the boats dimensions using mathematical formulas 
the computers tell visitors whether their redesigned boat will 
float and whether the king would have been satisfied 
two years and 1000 oak trees were invested in the vasa the 
ships commanders simply loaded 64 heavy cannons on board hoisted 
sail and hoped for the best 
shipbuilding was not an exact science in those days and there 
are several possible reasons why the vasa turned out badly even 
though it was neither larger than other ships of the period nor of 
a radically different design 
one of the factors might have been the death during the project 
of the dutch shipbulder who supervised the job another may have 
been an order by gustavus to add a second gun deck thus making the 
vasa unusually topheavy 
a royal inquiry found no one guilty in the ships sinking the 
court could not determine whether the vasa was too narrow below the 
waterline too heavy above it or whether it needed more ballast to 
make it sail upright 
the new museum tells the story with slides and ship models 
frescoes and fullsize human carvings recall intellectual and 
political themes of the 17th century and give the flavor of life 
in old stockholm 
some visitors have criticized the building which they say is as 
poorly designed as the vasa the museum resembles a copperclad 
barn with masts inside some exhibits are dimly lit and some 
explanatory labels are placed at kneelevel 
but the museum allows visitors to see the vasa close up from 
all sides and on several levels 
the ship came largely intact from its centuries in the mud 
because the baltic seas water has little salt and woodeating 
marine worms dont live there 
its oncegaudily painted hull is blackened but hundreds of 
sculptures that adorned her stern and upper decks survived in 
remarkable detail 
objects recovered from the vasa on view include sailors 
clothes tools and games visitors can walk through a replica of 
the upper gun deck and examine a 23footlong model of the vasa 
which took 13000 hours to build and shows the 20000 nails used in 
the original 
swedish engineer anders franzen an amateur marine archeologist 
found the vasa in 1956 the vessel was raised five years later and 
placed until two years ago in a temporary aluminum shed visited by 
more than 11 million people 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

