<TEXT>
a strong demand for cattle hides used to make 
shoes in several east asian countries has translated into extra 
money for us beef producers according to agriculture department 
economists 
its a package deal though because hides are simply the 
outside wrappers for cattle and its what inside that counts most 
for american beef eaters and producers 
for example according to analysts in the departments economic 
research service if an 1100pound steer sold for 70 per 100 
pounds of live weight it brought its owner 770 
as a rule of thumb the hide is worth about 1 per pound with 
its weight at around 55 pounds on the average so 55 of the 770 
would be for the hide 
when cattle go to the packing plant they are paid for on the 
basis of live weight that is what the farmer rancher or feedlot 
operator is paid as owner of the animals 
the packer kills and separates various parts including the red 
meat for consumers tallow hides and other offal 
economist larry duewer said that as of june 9 the offal value in 
a typical slaughter steer averaged about 850 per 100 pounds of 
the animals live weight that included the hide 
if cattle are selling for 70 per hundredweight 850 of 
that is the hide and offal value and i think at least half of that 
850 is hides duewer said thursday in a telephone interview 
the producer is paid on the basis of the live weight of the 
whole animal consumers however buy only the edible parts of 
cattle which are segregated by the packer from the offal and have 
their own prices 
thus duewer said higher prices for hides are not supposed to 
be linked with the cost of red meat at the supermarket but the 
hide market is important to the cattle producer 
it definitely gives him more money and technically it 
shouldnt affect the price of beef for consumers he said 
christine bolling another usda economist says the american 
demand for highpriced sports shoes has helped buoy the hide 
market particularly exports to south korea and taiwan 
those countries import the hides make them into shoes and ship 
them back to the united states these are quality athletic footwear 
selling for 50 and up 
south korea second only to italy as a shoe exporter shipped 
more than 150 million pairs valued at 23 billion to the united 
states in 1988 compared with 25 million pairs in 1982 bolling 
said in the july issue of farmline magazine 
taiwan shipped 120 million pairs of leather shoes to the united 
states in 1988 those had an export value of 14 billion 
japan is the third major importer of us cattle hides among the 
asian nations but its footwear emphasis differs from that of south 
korea and taiwan since it focuses on meeting domestic footwear 
needs 
with rising per capita disposable incomes the japanese are 
demanding more upscale products like leather shoes bolling 
said 
