<TEXT>
in the event of chemical warfare the air 
force will clean its military equipment with hot soapy water the 
navy will use a bleaching agent similar to most household products 
but the army and marine corps according to a longstanding 
policy will opt for a decontaminant solution that six years ago 
ate through an electronic cable on an m1 tank in about a half hour 
the practice of using socalled ds2 prompted congressional 
investigators on thursday to urge defense secretary dick cheney to 
direct the two services to find a safer cheaper alternative 
it also drew the ire of the chairman of the house government 
operations subcommittee on environment energy and natural 
resources who berated an army brigadier general for his response 
to the investigators findings 
based on the general accounting office report the testimony 
it appears there are equally effective and less hazardous 
alternatives that are already available said rep mike synar 
dokla can i get a commitment from you the army will consider 
alternatives without waiting 10 or 20 years to develop a new 
decontaminant 
brig gen david a nydam commanding general of the us 
chemical research development and engineering center said he 
could not commit the army to such action like that 
we have looked at all the alternatives ds2 continues to be 
the best that there is available nydam said 
synar responded angrily 
if you dont have the serious commitment to change the 
potential environmental health exposure to our fighting men and 
women you need to check your credentials at the door the 
congressman said 
it could be literally another agent orange sitting out 
there he said 
the criticism came as representatives from gao the 
investigative arm of congress detailed serious problems with the 
solution ranging from leaking containers that were improperly 
stored to sales to private individuals who were never informed of 
the hazards 
in defense of their selection army officials said that unlike 
the navy and air force the services forces live in the field and 
must take their equipment with them 
this requires the availability of a decontaminant which can 
effectively be used in an efficient and immediate manner in 
locations where water may be severely limited in availability 
nydam said 
the military services have purchased about 5 million gallons of 
ds2 since the early 1960s with the army requiring the largest 
amount 666000 gallons at a cost of nearly 18 million 
the chemical solution is manufactured by dalden corp of 
roanoke texas and poly research of holtsville ny 
the gao found that ds2 is toxic and highly corrosive and can 
cause severe burns liver damage and reproductive or birth defects 
based on the problems the air force and navy have opted for less 
toxic alternatives 
the army despite its own tests that show bleaches were just as 
effective as ds2 continues to stick with the chemical solution 
in addition the gao found that at five of the us facilities 
the ds2 was improperly stored and in some cases the cans were 
leaking 
at fort sill okla the chemical was stored with supertropical 
bleach a combination that could set off an explosion meanwhile 
at fort lewis wash cans of ds2 were stored in a shed without 
walls exposing the material to the elements 
nydam said the army was aware of the problem and was correcting 
the mistakes at the storage facility 
the gao also found that the army sold cans of the chemical to 
private citizens but failed to provide them with material safety 
data sheets which identify the health and environmental hazards 
associated with ds2 
