optimistic the search for other solar systems can proceed 
the search is important because if lots of stars have planets 
then the chances that some of those planets might have life on them 
is better and ultimately the chance there might be intelligent 
life somewhere is greater he said 
even if it worked perfectly the hubble couldnt detect life on 
other planets but westphal said it could bring scientists one step 
closer to the answer to one of the most interesting of all 
questions is there anybody else out there 
despite the focusing problem the main camera still should be 
able to search for planets outside our solar system five times more 
effectively than any telescope on earth westphal said 
test photographs show that about 85 percent of the light that 
enters the camera is not properly focused but about 15 percent 
is where it belongs and makes a nice little sharp image he 
explained so we anticipate that we can probably use that little 
sharp core to watch for stars to wobble 
trying to see a jupitersized planet orbiting a nearby star 
often has been compared to a person trying to see a speck of dust 
miles away when that speck is sitting next to a 1000watt light 
bulb 
during the past decade astronomers found indirect evidence that 
more than three dozen stars seem to be surrounded either by 
flattened disks of dust possibly young solar systems in the 
process or forming planets or by planetlike objects known as 
brown dwarfs 
westphal said plans call for hubble to observe only one of 
those barnards star which has a tantalizing wobble to it 
the others are too far for hubble to observe 
the stars westphal hopes the telescope can observe are all 
considered nearby or within 10 light years of earth thats 
almost 60 trillion miles 
