congressional conferees are refusing to 
approve trial us participation in international oil spill 
accords thereby clearing a major hurdle in legislation to 
compensate victims of accidents 
the conferees set to meet again july 12 now can turn to the 
two remaining issues in the bill amounts of penalties to be 
assessed against those responsible for spills and whether to 
require doublehulled vessels 
the conference by voice vote on thursday did approve 
nonbinding language stating its in the best interests of the 
united states to participate in two international compensation 
agreements 
but senate conferees refused to approve actual membership 
partly because the chamber has been unable to exercise its right to 
approve international treaties 
the senators led by majority leader george mitchell dmaine 
also wanted to preserve rights of states to impose their own 
liability rules for spills in their waters 
two international agreements called protocols were negotiated 
in 1984 and 41 countries have ratified them but they wont become 
operational unless the united states approves its participation 
rep gerry e studds dmass proposed that the united states 
join the international agreements on a trial basis for five years 
if they were modified to comply with federal and state liability 
laws 
if the modifications were not made at the end of five years the 
nation would have withdrawn from the agreements 
the house conferees unanimously approved the proposal but the 
senate members voted unanimously for rejection 
the house side then came back with the sense of congress 
advisory provisions that won acceptance 
with no international agreements alaska for example was able 
to impose unlimited liability on the operators of the 
usregistered exxon valdez the tanker that spilled 11 million 
gallons of crude oil in prince william sound last year 
alaska could have held the operators of a foreignflag vessel to 
the same standard but would not be able to if the international 
limits were in force 
under the international accords those hurt by an oil spill 
could first seek compensation from insurers for the responsible 
party with a ceiling of 75 million 
the applicant then could seek up to 260 million from an 
international fund that already has been established without us 
participation 
as a third step those affected could try to tap a us domestic 
fund that would allow collections of up to 1 billion per spill 
the domestic fund already has been established from a 
nickelabarrel fee on oil transporters although no money has been 
spent it would become operational under the new legislation 
