<TEXT>
changes in tampons have led to a 93 percent drop 
in toxic shock syndrome since 1980 when the disease was linked to 
tampon use federal officials say 
just 61 cases of toxic shock syndrome were reported last year 
compared with 890 cases in 1980 the centers for disease control 
said thursday 
toxic shock a bacterial infection found most often in 
menstruationage women was linked especially to the most absorbent 
brands of tampons 
cdc researchers are convinced that the decrease is real and 
that tampon characteristics had been much of the problem said dr 
anne schuchat a cdc infectious disease specialist 
our initial concern was that after the public attention and 
the media attention went away people were not bothering to 
report cases she said 
but a 198687 study which actively sought to locate cases 
across several states found one case per 100000 women between the 
ages of 14 and 44 a tenfold drop from the 1980 rate schuchat 
said 
the united states recorded 45 cases of toxic shock in 
menstruationage women last year and 16 nonmenstruation cases a 
decade ago 812 of the 890 cases were associated with menstruation 
three important developments occurred in tampons in the 1980s 
the cdc said 
the brand implicated in many early cases rely was taken off 
the market 
tampons became less absorbent in 1980 42 percent of tampon 
users used very high absorbency products the type considered most 
risky for toxic shock by 1986 it was 1 percent 
the material makeup of tampons changed rely consisted of 
polyester foam and carboxymethylcellulose tampons containing 
polyacrylate were withdrawn in 1985 and current tampons are made 
with cotton or rayon 
the withdrawal of rely and the drop in use of highabsorbency 
tampons correlate with a marked decrease in incidence of 
menstrual toxic shock syndrome though its still unclear why 
those types of tampons increased the risk the report said 
the food and drug administration declared last year that tampon 
makers must use uniform labeling terms for absorbency ranges 
allowing women to compare brands federal health officials 
recommend that women who use tampons rather than sanitary napkins 
which have no known risk of toxic shock should use the lowest 
absorbency product effective for them 
in its report the cdc said other factors may have contributed 
to the drop in toxic shock after the highly publicized concerns 
over the disease tampon use may have decreased and milder cases 
may not be reported as often 
</TEXT>
