<TEXT>
about 660000 union members in this 
country of 48 million people are threatening to launch a crippling 
sympathy walkout if the us banana giant chiquita does not raise 
wages for its striking workers 
the chiquita strike that began thursday is the latest and 
potentially most serious labor unrest to hit the 5monthold 
administration of president rafael leonardo callejas 
chiquitas 10000 union members including banana cutters 
railway workers and administrative personnel averaging about 15 a 
day struck for a 60 percent salary increase paralyzing operations 
the 70000strong national federation of workers unions which 
includes the chiquita workers said members of other unions would 
begin walking off their job today beginning with 2000 texaco 
refinery workers the refinery supplies the entire nation 
other labor groups including the 600000member workers 
confederation have said they will strike if chiquita refuses to 
negotiate 
the president of the national legislature rodolfo irias navas 
said the labor unrest could destabilize honduras the poorest 
nation in the hemisphere after haiti with an annual per capita 
income of only 740 
the crisis created by unionism is putting the stability of the 
government in danger he said in a telephone interview 
workers at chiquita brands international inc make an average 
1532 a day and have not had a raise for six years while 
inflation has climbed 50 percent annually their union asked the 
company for a higher pay in october 
