<TEXT>
environmental officials worked behind closed doors 
today to reach a compromise on an agreement to ban chemicals that 
destroy the earths fragile ozone shield 
a major issue is a proposal that would ban a broad range of 
chemicals and establish a global environmental fund to help 
developing nations switch to technology that would protect the 
environment 
when the meeting opened june 19 there appeared to be broad 
consensus on many recommended changes to the montreal protocol of 
1987 
the international treaty controls chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs 
and other ozonedepleting chemicals used in electronics foam 
blowing fire extinguishers aerosols and refrigeration 
scientific evidence has left little doubt that the ozone layer 
which shields the earth from harmful ultraviolet rays is eroding 
virtually all of the nearly 100 countries at the meeting recognize 
that the problem is global and lifethreatening 
prospects for agreement seemed good but coming negotiations on 
global warming will be more complex and the current conference was 
viewed as a dress rehearsal 
delegates said that in working sessions countries often 
appeared more concerned about defending their own interests and 
that a conflict was emerging between developed nations of the 
northern hemisphere and poorer southern countries 
there was definitely more northsouth rhetoric here than in 
montreal said richard benedick who headed the us delegation 
at the montreal conference and is in london as an observer 
participants from china a major cfc consumer said it would 
recommend that beijing sign the treaty but india issued an 
ultimatum saying it would sign only if developed nations 
guaranteed to make alternative technology available 
maneka gandhi indias environment minister said the new global 
ozone fund predicted to be worth at least 160 million was not 
enough 
money is irrelevant if we dont have access to knowledge 
survival is about the spread of knowledge she told western 
reporters we did not destroy the ozone layer you have done that 
already dont ask us to pay the price 
the montreal protocol signed by 56 nations called for halving 
the use of eight chemicals including cfcs by 1996 
participants at the current conference were expected to agree to 
a ban on other chemicals including halons and carbon 
tetrachloride both used in firefighting by the year 2000 when 
cfcs are to be phased out entirely 
the united states and environmentalists were united in their 
wish to add to the protocol the new chemical substitutes being 
developed to replace cfcs these chemicals called hcfcs also 
destroy ozone although at a much slower rate 
the european community led by britain france and spain are 
all heavily involved in hcfc production and opposed adding them to 
the treaty 
conference sources said agreement had been reached to mention 
the cfc alternatives in a nonbinding resolution 
still this will be an extraordinary achievement said 
benedick a senior fellow of the conservation foundation and world 
wildlife fund on assignment for the state department 
the environmental fund is a tremendous breakthrough we know 
ultraviolet radiation will kill millions and millions of people 
so progress toward saving the ozone shield is not a trivial 
achievement 
