<TEXT>
an error in the grinding and polishing of the 
main mirrors aboard the hubble space telescope has been pinpointed 
as the cause of a focus flaw that crippled the 15 billion 
orbiting observatory 
an official of hughes danbury optical co which manufactured 
the mirrors said thursday night that experiments with signals from 
the hubble have confirmed that a mistake was made in the tedious 
threeyear process of making the primary and secondary hubble 
mirrors 
with fairly high certainty we have concluded that the 
shape of one of the mirrors is not correct said terence facey a 
hughes danbury engineer who helped nasa isolate the source of the 
hubble focusing problem 
he said it was not known which mirror is flawed but that may be 
discovered by searching the connecticut companys records of tests 
conducted during the months of grinding and polishing required to 
turn footthick spherical glass blanks into the telescope mirrors 
those records and equipment used in making the mirrors have been 
impounded by nasa as the first step in an investigation of what 
went wrong with the expensive satellite the agencys chief 
scientist lennard fisk told a senate committee today 
but fisk said he was somewhat concerned that we are going to 
try and reconstruct an event that took place a decade ago and he 
sought to put the best face on the problem telling sen al gore 
dtenn that much excellent scientific work will be unaffected 
we will adjust the observing program to emphasize the things 
that hubble does well today such as ultraviolet imagery fisk 
said 
two senators who oversee the space program meanwhile reacted 
angrily to news of the hubble focusing flaw and ordered hearings on 
the mistake 
im very outraged at what has happened to hubble said sen 
barbara mikulski dmd they have had 10 years to put this 
together and spent 28 billion to be able to get it right 
now we find that the hubble telescope has a cataract she 
said 
the national aeronautics and space administration has said the 
telescope cost 15 billion plus 600 million for operations and 
maintenance 
sen albert gore dtenn chairman of the senate subcommittee 
on science technology and space called a hearing on the hubble 
problem for today with nasas chief scientist lennard fisk as 
the lead witness 
mikulski said she and rep bob traxler dmich also plan an 
investigation 
nasa engineers discovered the focusing flaw in hubble after they 
were unable to coax the telescope into capturing crisp clean 
photos of distant stars 
facey said he assisted the space agency in the tests and helped 
to confirm that the problem was in one of the two mirrors it was a 
tough job he said in a telephone interview its always 
difficult to conclude that youve made a mistake 
meanwhile the new york times reported in todays editions that 
nasa decided against using topsecret groundbased military 
testing equipment that likely would have detected the problem 
before the hubble was launched the times quoted a scientist 
involved in the agencys deliberations who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
facey said that although the main hubble mirror can be adjusted 
slightly from the ground by moving actuators that cause the glass 
to flex the system will not correct the focus enough to eliminate 
the problem he said only about 10 percent of the focus error could 
be corrected 
nasa has started a formal investigation of the hubble problem 
lew allen head of the jet propulsion laboratory in pasadena 
calif was named chairman of an engineer review committee that 
space agency officials said will include outside experts 
meanwhile astronomers are scrambling to find ways to salvage 
some use from the hubble despite the loss of precise focus 
ed weiler a nasa scientist said three of the five instruments 
on board will be able to get 50 to 75 percent of their planned 
scientific studies 
two of the instruments are spectrometers which can measure the 
temperature composition and movement of stars another instrument 
a photometer will be able to measure stellar brightness and to 
look for black holes 
most seriously hurt by the loss of focus are two cameras 
designed to capture visual images of distant stars galaxies and 
other objects 
the 40 million widefield planetary camera will be of only 
small use without a precise focus and weiler called it a 
significant loss 
a replacement widefield camera is scheduled to be installed in 
hubble in june 1993 weiler said a new optical lens which will 
correct the focus flaw from the mirror will allow the new camera 
to take sharp pictures 
the fifth hubble instrument a faint object camera that can 
gather images in invisible ultraviolet light will be able to do 
about 50 percent of its planned studies he said 
weiler said that though the focus flaw causes big problems for 
hubble the error actually is minute he said the telescope misses 
precise focus by a distance of only 4 percent of the diameter of a 
human hair 
</TEXT>
