<TEXT>
often lavish to the extreme the japanese wedding 
isnt just ceremony its theater 
enter a prince dressed in black and red silken robes with the 
curved black tailpiece of his royal cap bobbing with every step and 
a mace held straight up before his chest 
a few steps behind a princesstobe her hair coiffed in 
ancient court fashion her kimono a rainbow of nearly a dozen 
layers colored green burgundy maroon and orange 
the stage a quiet mysterious shrine tucked away in a small 
wood behind the moat and high stone walls of the imperial palace 
then there is a cinderella plot line the sipping of sacred rice 
wine and the reading of solemn vows to a sun goddess 
it is the ultimate in japanese nuptials the royal wedding 
on friday the 1 million affair was for prince aya emperor 
akihitos youngest son and his college sweetheart 23yearold 
graduate student kiko kawashima only the second commoner to marry 
into japans imperial family 
while on a smaller scale many wedding customs practiced by the 
average japanese reflect those of the imperial family 
possibly because the wedding was the first for an imperial 
family member since 1984 and the first for a prince of ayas 
status in nearly three decades japans media rushed to chronicle 
it and the trends it spawned 
newspaper readers have been informed of hurried engagements of 
famous entertainers booming sales of pearl necklaces like the one 
princess kiko was wearing and rising prices for stock shares in 
bridal companies 
a rental business even sprang up for the bulky junihitoe 
style kimono that princess kiko wore the traditional japanese 
attire now is reserved mainly for special occasions 
the rental fee for the kimono makeup and wig is 2600 only a 
fraction of the 58000 the average japanese will spend on a 
wedding and honeymoon says the japan institute for social and 
economic affairs 
miss kawashima began friday in a pink dress and hat became 
princess kiko in the multilayered kimono and then greeted her 
imperial inlaws in a white evening dress replete with 
diamondstudded tiara and necklace 
most brides in japan change clothes at least once during their 
reception often beginning with a kimono and switching to a 
cocktail dress the reappearance made as a mist from dry ice 
spreads across the hall adds a theatrical touch 
after the end of world war ii nearly all weddings were 
performed at shrines to the gods of shinto japans indigenous 
religion sakesipping before the shinto gods however ancient it 
may sound was an innovation made for the wedding of ayas 
greatgrandfather in 1900 
shintostyle weddings still are the most popular accounting for 
55 percent to 60 percent of the total says keiko shimizu of the 
private wedding advice center but they may be on the way out 
young women these days prefer church weddings not because of 
any particular religious beliefs but because they want to wear 
wedding dresses ms shimizu said they are used to 
westernstyle clothes and just dont feel comfortable in kimono any 
more 
