<TEXT>
a 71yearold vermont supreme court 
justice is stepping down from the bench after successfully fighting 
against the states mandatory retirement law 
justice louis peck said he has notified gov madeleine kunin of 
his intention to retire effective oct 1 
the state decided earlier this month not to appeal a federal 
court ruling upholding pecks right to remain despite a 
constitutional provision that all judges in vermont retire at age 
70 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals ruled this spring that a 
federal law restricting mandatory retirement covers appointed state 
judges 
when peck turned 70 in december 1988 he refused to retire 
i felt strongly that if a person is in good health that person 
ought to be allowed to remain on the bench peck said thursday 
i kind of have mixed emotions my primary motivation was to test 
the law 
i have done that and now i feel i can retire he said 
the federal appeals court decision allowed peck to remain on the 
bench until his term ends in three years 
peck is considered the most conservative member of the states 
highest court he has written several stinging dissents to court 
decisions that he felt unfairly usurped the power of the 
legislature 
peck was appointed to the court in 1981 by thengov richard 
snelling a republican at the time peck was vermonts chief 
assistant attorney general 
his decision to retire means that kunin a democrat can appoint 
his replacement before she leaves office in january in doing so 
kunin will have named three of the courts five justices 
peck said his decision was prompted in part by early retirement 
incentives being offered in state government the program is part 
of an effort to reduce the number of state employees 
