<TEXT>
police smashed open a door of the 
agriculture ministry with a sledgehammer tonight and stormed into 
the building to end a threeday sitin strike by farmers seeking 
guaranteed prices for their goods 
officers broke open a locked ministry door shortly before 730 
pm and scores of uniformed officers entered the building in 
central warsaw 
the move came after efforts to persuade the farmers to leave of 
their own volition failed it was not immediately known if officers 
encountered any resistance inside or if there were any arrests 
the government steadfastly had refused to negotiate with the 
protesters while the occupation continued 
earlier in the day police who had ringed the ministry withdrew 
after the 600 farmers had agreed to admit employees 
the police wagons had roared off on a ranking officers signal 
as the ministry workers filed in through an iron gate hung with a 
strike banner a parliament delegation also was admitted to meet 
with the farmers 
the growers are demanding minimum prices for their products as a 
shelter from the governments shock economic reform program they 
occupied the ministry wednesday afternoon following a protest march 
through warsaw they shut the building to employees on thursday 
agricultural minister czeslaw janicki and his deputies were 
permitted in this morning as the workers waited outside two dozen 
police vehicles then surrounded the building 
the government conditioned the start of serious negotiations on 
the farmers allowing the resumption of normal work at the ministry 
and ending their sitin 
the farmers who clustered in several ministry conference rooms 
said they would not conduct talks until the police were removed 
but they appeared divided over whether to agree to admit the 
workers and reversed their decision several times before allowing 
them in at midafternoon 
polish peasant party chairman roman bartoszcze met with the 
protesters late thursday to report on his discussions with prime 
minister tadeusz mazowiecki president wojciech jaruzelski and 
solidarity leader lech walesa 
walesa who was to return tonight from vienna said he would be 
available to help resolve the conflict bartoszcze said 
the solidarity leaders personal appeal won suspensions of the 
two other serious challenges to the mazowiecki reform program a 
strike by railway workers that disrupted transport across northwest 
poland in may and a blockade of the main warsawgdansk highway by 
dairy farmers in midjune 
mazowiecki will not give up on issues linked with guaranteed 
minimum prices and there will be no talks as long as farmers are 
occupying the ministerial building bartoszcze said according to 
the official pap news agency 
the farmers seek the governmentset minimum prices as a buffer 
against the effects of postcommunist polands drive to create a 
market economy out of the centralized socialized system of the 
last four decades 
a complex web of economic factors has pushed down farm prices 
one problem is that consumption has fallen in the face of price 
increases of up to 1000 percent in a year there is also a 
competitive glut of food donations from western nations who rushed 
to offer support to the new government 
the mazowiecki cabinet has repeatedly rejected demands for 
special treatment of any sector of the economy it has also refused 
to speak with railway workers or dairy farmers under the pressure 
of strike saying yielding once would produce a torrent of requests 
from other groups 
the government compares demands for minimum farm prices to the 
system of subsidies that the communist regime used to satisfy 
farmers while keeping consumer prices well below the actual cost of 
production 
the reform program cut most subsidies lifted price controls 
let interest rates rise to reflect the level of inflation and 
opened the economy to private ventures 
