<TEXT>
about 2000 victims of the 1984 bhopal 
gas disaster gathered near the home of prime minister vp singh on 
friday and demanded money and medical relief 
i want justice i want something 60yearold azghar ali 
cried feebly his voice lost in the crowds shouting 
the victims once again came from their central indian hometown 
to demand faster economic relief and medical aid to help them fight 
the debilitating effects of methyl isocynate gas 
the chemical leaked from a pesticide plant of union carbide 
corp in bhopal on dec 3 1984 killing more than 3000 people and 
injuring about 20000 others in the surrounding slums most of the 
victims were poor laborers 
ali a sign painter lived near the factory and was sleeping 
when the gas enveloped his shantytown 
today ali a bundle of bones and mottled skin cannot work 
because he cannot walk 100 yards without wheezing uncontrollably 
he lives in a tin shed survives on the charity of his neighbors 
and waits for government relief 
compensation suits against the usbased multinational have 
been held up for six years because of litigation in indian courts 
and changing government policies the victims have received only 
88 from the indian government that was distributed immediately 
after the disaster 
the government of rajiv gandhi singhs predecessor reached a 
supreme courtsupervised settlement with union carbide in february 
1989 and agreed to accept 470 million as compensation for the 
500000 claimants 
the government orginally sued union carbide for 3 billion 
several newspapers and political activists called the 1989 
settlement a sellout subsequent petitions in the supreme court 
delayed disbursement of the money 
singhs government which took office in december said it will 
challenge the 470 million settlement and reopen the case in an 
effort to pin criminal responsibility on union carbide criminal 
charges were withdrawn when the gandhi government accepted the 470 
million settlement from the company based in danbury conn 
on march 5 singhs government said it would pay interim 
compensation of 12 per month to each of about 500000 people 
living near the site of the gas leak the supreme court later asked 
the government to pay an additional 44 as monthly compensation to 
3110 totally disabled people 
but that has not helped ali yet 
the speed of disbursement is so slow that at the current pace 
it will take at least two years before all the victims start 
getting relief said abdul jabbar khan who organized the 
protesters train journey from bhopal 355 miles south of new delhi 
khan who has organized dozens of protest marches in bhopal and 
visits to new delhi said only 42000 beneficiaries have received 
money so far 
on friday khan convener of bhopal gas affected womens 
industrial group presented a memorandum at the prime ministers 
residence the marchers were stopped a halfmile away by a police 
barricade they camped on the road waiting for singhs reaction 
we just hope to get something from vp singh the rest is on 
allah said parveen jahan 25 whose only child died in infancy a 
few months after the gas leak 
she said she suffered a miscarriage a month ago because the gas 
has made me incapable of bearing children 
other women rushed to mrs jahan as she began sobbing silently 
her tears falling on crumpled medical records of her dead baby and 
of her miscarried fetus 
