hoped his latest letter to president bush on the peace process 
would open a new chapter for the middle east an aide to shamir 
said 
the letter is viewed in israel as the rightwing governments 
first formal acceptance of certain proposals by secretary of state 
james a baker iii aimed at holding israelipalestinian peace talks 
in cairo 
sources in the bush administration said officials are taking a 
close look at shamirs letter and may set up a meeting between 
baker and israeli foreign minister david levy 
at issue is the future of the 17 million palestinians living in 
the west bank and gaza strip that israel captured in the 1967 
middle east war 
shamir sent the letter in response to one from president bush 
inquiring about the prime ministers intentions now that he has 
formed a new government the last israeli government headed by 
shamir collapsed in march in disagreement over whether to approve 
bakers formula for israelipalestinian talks 
israel has proposed holding elections for palestinians to select 
negotiators for an interim peace settlement of limited selfrule 
bakers proposals were raised last year as a way to start 
implementation of the plan but negotiations became mired in 
israels objection to talks with the palestine liberation 
organization which israel considers a terrorist organization and 
palestinians consider their legitimate representative 
pazner said shamirs very lengthy sevenpage document to 
bush this week proposed a new method for choosing palestinian 
negotiators acceptable to israel 
shamir wrote that every palestinian living in the territories 
can take part in a palestinian delegation on a namebyname 
basis pazner said 
that formula is seen as a possible way to sidestep israels 
objections to speaking with representatives of the plo and israels 
