<TEXT>
representatives from 56 countries on friday 
approved a 240 million environmental fund for developing nations 
and established a ban on chemicals that deplete the earths 
protective ozone layer by the year 2000 
but many countries accused the united states of footdragging in 
negotiating changes to a 1987 montreal protocol which controls the 
production and use of ozonedepleting chemicals 
cabinet ministers from at least 12 countries pointing to recent 
scientific studies on the speed in which the ozone layer is being 
destroyed urged a ban on halons and chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs 
by 1997 
the united states japan and the soviet union insisted the 
deadline for such a ban be the year 2000 delaying the ban for 
three years would allow the release of 11 billion more tons of 
chemicals into the stratosphere environmentalists said 
the 1987 protocol had called for a 50 percent cut in the 
chemicals by 2000 
like that protocol fridays actions have no penalties for 
violations and no enforcement powers 
the new treaty bans chcs by that year and increases the list of 
controlled chemicals from eight to 20 
we believe it is necessary and possible to do better than this 
timetable said west german environment minister klaus topfer 
unfortunately three countries refused to go along 
william reilly administrator for the us environmental 
protection agency said he was pleased with agreement 
i think it was a very successful conference he said when 
the treaty parties meet again in 1992 they will see if a case can 
be made for accelerating the schedule he said 
the conference agreed to a phaseout schedule that would cut 
cfcs by 20 percent in 1993 and 50 percent in 1995 before the final 
ban the 30page amendment to the montreal protocol also banned 
carbon tetrachloride by the end of the century and eliminated 
methyl chloroform by 2005 
in another move the conference approved an unprecedented 240 
million fund to assist developing nations build industries that do 
not rely on chemicals that deplete the ozone 
the fund sponsored by developed nations is seen by many as a 
model for solving other more costly environmental problems 
china and india will each receive 40 million over the next 
three years after they sign the protocol which they have said they 
will do bringing those two populous countries into the treaty was 
considered vital 
the fund will be controlled by an executive committee made up of 
developing and industrialized nations that will each serve 
threeyear terms 
cfcs used in refrigeration insulation cleaning solvents and 
as aerosol propellents rise into the stratosphere where they break 
down in constituent chemical parts one of these chlorine 
destroys the thin shield of ozone that filters out harmful 
ultraviolet rays and helps preserve the earths flora 
about 100 countries attended the twoweek conference only the 
56 parties to the montreal protocol were allowed to vote on the 
agreement 
the conference was seen as a precursor to more difficult 
negotiations that will take place soon on global warming and 
reducing the use of fossil fuels 
</TEXT>
