<TEXT>
in a rare show of unity quebecs premier and a 
provincial opposition leader agreed friday to establish a 
nonpartisan parliamentary commission to map out quebecs political 
future 
at a crucial time in its history quebec is united premier 
robert bourassa said following a 90minute meeting with the head of 
parti quebecois jacques parizeau 
the meeting was in response to the defeat of the meech lake 
accord which would have designated quebec a distinct society 
all 10 provinces and the federal government had to ratify the 
constitutional amendment by saturday midnight but newfoundland 
suspended debate on the issue and the accord expired 
the accord was an attempt to gain frenchspeaking quebecs 
signature on canadas 1982 constitution it had little practical 
impact but became a symbol of enormous importance to the 65 
million quebecois who make up onefourth of canadas population 
what we have done is an important first step in defining what 
quebec wants not as far as the rest of canada is concerned but 
what quebec wants as far as quebec is concerned said parizeau 
the parliamentary commission will be composed of representatives 
of labor business universities municipalities and members of 
political parties 
the leaders of the two parties will meet with their caucuses 
july 10 to set guidelines for the commission which will travel 
around the province to sound the opinions of quebecois on a variety 
of issues that include some quebecers desire to secede from canada 
the leaders said they hoped the commission would begin work this 
fall and produce a nonbinding report by the end of the year 
both leaders said it would be up to bourassa to use the 
commissions recommendations as a basis for a referendum an 
election or as a bargaining chip to resume negotiations with the 
federal government over possibly reconsideration of a special 
status for quebec within canadas federation 
