government forces killed 31 tamil 
rebels in battles friday and the bodies of 14 policemen were 
discovered in a mass grave military officials said 
the officials speaking on condition of anonymity said two 
soldiers were also killed in the renewed round of fighting in sri 
lankas sevenyearold civil war which has engulfed the island 
nations north and east where the ethnic tamil minority 
predominates 
the latest deaths raise to 1764 the number of combatants killed 
since fighting between tamil guerrillas and government forces 
resumed june 11 after a 13month ceasefire 
an undetermined number of civilians also have died 
military officials reported several battles in the east and 
said at least 18 rebels were killed in search operations conducted 
by the army 
also in the east the bodies of 14 policemen who were shot to 
death were found thursday the officials disclosed friday 
the liberation tigers of tamil eelam rebels overran a string of 
police stations along the eastern coast starting june 11 after a 
tamil man in the port city of batticaloa told the rebels he had 
been manhandled by sinhalese police 
at least 850 policemen were captured by the tamil tiger rebels 
officials have said at least 330 of the policemen have been 
killed and the fate of the others is unknown 
government forces launched an offensive after the police 
stations were captured forcing the rebels to retreat into the 
jungles and swamps in the east military officials believe the 
tigers retreat may be a tactical move to launch a protracted 
guerrilla war 
in the north at least 13 rebels and two soldiers were killed in 
a gunbattle in the district of vavuniya the officials said 
fighting also continued around jaffna fort an army installation 
in the heart of rebel territory the officials said 
at least 225 policemen and soldiers have been holed up in the 
fort since the fighting started 
loss of the fort would be a major blow to the government which 
now has only four military installations in the north under its 
control 
in the east authorities clamped a curfew on batticaloa and 
began housetohouse searches for rebels residents said 
a tamil doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
soldiers ordered all males aged 12 to 50 to report to military 
officials in the predominantly tamil town once a rebel stronghold 
while thousands of men gathered at schools churches mosques 
and temples the soldiers conducted housetohouse searches said 
another resident who also spoke on condition of anonymity 
the sri lankan army and police are dominated by sinhalese whom 
the tamils accuse of discrimination 
ethnic sinhalese who are mostly buddhists comprise 75 percent 
of the population while the predominantly hindu tamils comprise 18 
percent of the country 
at least 12700 people have been killed since the rebels took up 
arms in 1983 
