police used a sledgehammer to break into 
the agriculture ministry on friday and ended a 3dayold sitin by 
hundreds of farmers demanding guaranteed prices for their products 
officers broke open a locked ministry door shortly before 730 
pm scores of police carrying truncheons then entered the building 
in central warsaw 
several hundred farmers walking in a peaceful procession came 
out about a halfhour after police entered they carried a protest 
banner and were singing the patrioticreligious hymn rota and 
the national anthem 
a few demonstrators had to be pulled out but police said in 
general they did not encounter resistance they said there were no 
arrests or injuries 
the protesters later marched about a halfmile to a statue of 
preworld war ii peasant leader wincenty witos before dispersing 
the government said in a communique that it resorted to force 
only after efforts to persuade the farmers to leave of their own 
volition failed 
earlier in the day the estimated 600 protesters agreed to allow 
ministry employees to enter the building but the government 
steadfastly refused to negotiate with the farmers as long as they 
remained inside 
this form of protest is violating elementary principles of 
order in the country a government communique said 
the farmers are demanding minimum price guarantees for their 
products as shelter from the governments economic reform program 
which is turning polands centrally controlled socialist economy 
into a marketdriven system they occupied the government wednesday 
after a march through warsaw and closed the building to employees 
thursday 
agricultural minister czeslaw janicki and his deputies were 
permitted inside friday morning as the workers waited outside two 
dozen police vehicles then surrounded the building 
the farmers who clustered in several ministry conference rooms 
said they would not conduct talks until the police were removed 
but they appeared divided over whether to agree to admit the 
workers and reversed their decision several times before allowing 
them in at midafternoon 
curious spectators sometimes breaking into debate waited 
outside the entrance to the blocksquare ministry signs hung 
outside proclaimed there is no freedom without justice and 
we will never abandon the soil of our roots 
solidarity leader lech walesa returned to poland from vienna on 
friday and said he would be available if asked to help resolve the 
conflict 
the solidarity leaders personal appeal won suspensions of two 
other challenges to the reform program a strike by railway 
workers that disrupted transport across northwest poland in may 
and a blockade of the main warsawgdansk highway by dairy farmers 
in midjune 
the economic reform program cut most subsidies lifted price 
controls let interest rates rise to reflect the level of 
inflation and opened the economy to private ventures 
it has led to price increases of up to 1000 percent in a year 
leading to a drop in consumption there is also a glut of food 
donations from western nations which rushed to offer support to 
the new solidarityled government 
nearly half of polands 25 million private farms are plots of 
about 12 acres or less and farmers say they have neither the time 
nor the transport to seek competitive markets for their products 
polands leaders have repeatedly refused demands for special 
treatment by various sectors of the economy saying that yielding 
once would produce a torrent of requests from other groups 
the government compares demands for minimum farm prices to the 
system of subsidies that the communist regime used to pay farmers 
and keep consumer prices well below the actual cost of production 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

