<TEXT>
it has taken william finn nearly a decade to 
complete his musical trilogy about marvin a sexual sad sack who 
when we last saw him nine years ago had left an angry wife and a 
confused young son for a male lover 
but judging from the show that has found its way onto the tiny 
stage of offbroadways playwrights horizons the wait has been 
worth it the new 80minute musical which opened thursday is 
called falsettoland and its a compelling hugely entertaining 
piece of contemporary musical theater directed with energy and wit 
by james lapine 
but falsettoland is something more too darker and deeper 
than in trousers and march of the falsettos the first two 
marvin musicals this final installment of finns tale about modern 
manhattan life deals among other things with death and more 
specifically aids and finn with the help of the everresourceful 
lapine has pulled off the balancing act between satire and 
seriousness brilliantly 
the characters are much the same group finn brought to life in 
march of the falsettos 
the musical begins in 1981 where march of the falsettos 
ended theres marvin still as indecisive as ever equivocating 
over his relationship with whizzer that lover of yesteryear 
theres trina marvins embittered exwife and their son jason 
who has problems trying to accept his fathers sexual preferences 
and theres mendel marvins psychiatrist a man who had eventually 
married trina in march of the falsettos talk about confusing 
relationships 
finn has added two more characters marvins nextdoor 
neighbors two lesbians one is a doctor the other a caterer of 
kosher cuisine both occupations it turns out of increasing 
importance as the plot unfolds 
the story revolves around jasons bar mitzvah or rather his 
unwillingness to have a bar mitzvah and his parents squabbling 
over the celebration intertwined with their arguments is whizzers 
illness a fact finn faces unflinchingly 
as in the other two musicals marvin stands at the center of 
falsettoland in march of the falsettos marvin grew up 
or at least tried to in falsettoland he goes a step further 
accepting life and death his philosophy is anchored in one of 
finns more poignant lyrics we laugh we fumble we take it day 
by day what more can i say 
it turns out finn has a lot to say and some of it is very 
funny he has captured perfectly the frenzied selfcentered 
neuroses of new yorkers at work and play 
and without being didactic he deftly condenses as well as 
personalizes the history of aids in new york there are somber 
moments in the musical but they are never ponderous 
finns gift for melody overflows enhanced by michael starobins 
evocative orchestrations the composer jams some 17 numbers into 
the short musical which is mostly all sung finns lyrics are 
appropriate too sometimes surprisingly simple but affecting and 
at other times sassy and sophisticated 
as marvin michael rupert who also appeared in march of the 
falsettos turns nebbish into charming not an easy task 
ruperts marvin is a sympathetic appealing character instead of 
just a nerd 
faith prince handles the role of the exasperated exwife with 
skill a woman who could come off as the villain of the musical 
but instead earns our admiration as someone trying to keep sane 
while the rules keep changing 
chip zien as the psychiatrist serves as the evenings voice of 
reason and common sense he actually is the one person attuned to 
everyones problems stephen bogardus who has the shows best 
voice is fine as whizzer and danny gerard is surprisingly 
unaffected as the troubled but precocious jason heather macrae 
and janet metz offer distinctive portrayals as the solicitous 
nextdoor neighbors 
playwrights horizons long a champion of new plays is on 
something of a roll with musicals its last production once on 
this island was the best musical of last season that show moves 
to broadway next october and stephen sondheims new musical 
assassins opens at playwrights in november meanwhile its 
audiences will have much to savor in finns fascinating 
falsettoland 
</TEXT>
