<TEXT>
a federal appeals court on friday allowed an 
imprisoned member of the irish republican army to reapply for 
asylum in the united states to avoid deportation to northern 
ireland 
joseph doherty 35 has been imprisoned in new york for seven 
years he faces a life sentence in northern ireland for the 1980 
slaying of a british army officer and for a prison escape 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals overturned a june 1989 
ruling by us attorney general dick thornburgh denying doherty an 
asylum hearing 
the decision gives doherty the chance to try to prove his crimes 
were political that he faces severe persecution in northern 
ireland and should be granted refuge in the united states 
he is entitled to a hearing on his claim for political asylum 
and he may well be entitled to political asylum said dohertys 
attorney mary pike mr doherty is not going anywhere anytime 
soon certainly not to the united kingdom 
deborah corley a spokeswoman for the us attorneys office in 
new york said the government was reviewing the decision and had no 
immediate comment 
immigration laws allow political asylum if a foreigner can 
demonstrate a wellfounded fear of persecution on political 
religious racial or social grounds 
withholding deportation a separate action from asylum is 
mandatory if a person can show his life would be threatened in the 
other country 
doherty fled to new york in 1982 after several years on the run 
in ireland he was arrested by the fbi in 1983 and the british 
government requested his extradition 
a federal judge barred extradition in 1984 because dohertys 
crimes were political doherty has admitted that he took part in 
killing the army officer but said he did so for political reasons 
doherty has won decisions before two federal appeals courts two 
federal judges an immigration judge and three immigration appeals 
courts 
but the immigration court decisions were overturned by 
thenattorney general edwin meese iii and thornburgh 
the appeals court said the justice department intervention 
apparently was the first on grounds that asylum or deportation 
would endanger us foreign policy interests 
the threemember appeals court ruled that thornburgh exceeded 
his discretion in denying dohertys claim to asylum 
doherty in september 1986 asked to be deported to the republic 
of ireland where he faced a 10year prison sentence rather than 
life in prison in northern ireland the request was granted by a 
us immigration judge and upheld by an immigration appeals board 
despite objections by the justice department 
but meese in december 1988 overturned the request to be deported 
to ireland the federal board of immigration appeals subsequently 
allowed doherty to apply for asylum but not to change his 
designated country for deportation 
the appeals court friday also upheld meeses action but that 
ruling has less impact since doherty withdrew his request to be 
deported to ireland in 1986 
