<TEXT>
the loopy overthetop 1940s screen comedies of 
screenwriterdirector preston sturges have a manic energy and 
ironic style that identifies them even without a screen credit 
its fitting that american masters the distinguished pbs 
documentary series on american creative artists opens its fifth 
season tonight with the littleknown life of the first screenwriter 
to establish himself as a director 
a colleague frank capra said sturges was a strange guy 
carried his own hill with him i tell you 
where capras movies exalted the decent common man sturges 
lampooned a public willing to believe anything it was told 
his farces are filled with press agents politicians and 
confidence men who traffic in american values without believing in 
them despite their comic invention his plots always contained a 
savage bitter truth 
in the great mcginty brian donleavy plays a cynical bum who 
rises to wealth and political power through a corrupt system only 
to be tossed back into the gutter when he becomes an honest man 
in sullivans travels joel mccrea plays an idealistic film 
director who travels incognito to experience poverty and suffering 
then gets an overdose of it 
in the miracle at morgans creek betty hutton is a young 
woman who gives birth to sextuplets without knowing who their 
father is the wildly factitious story wrote critic james 
agee makes comic virtues of every censordodging necessity 
thanks to these devices the hays office has been either hypnotized 
into a liberality for which it should be thanked or has been raped 
in its sleep 
agee also wrote that sturges life read as dizzily as his 
screenplays 
the son of a chicago stockbroker preston had a miserable 
childhood trailing his flighty mother on a marathon of european 
museums and theaters 
his mother mary desti an intimate chum of isadora duncan gave 
the ballerina the long scarf that snagged on a sportscar wheel and 
broke her neck she also founded the paris cosmetics firm where 
sturges worked as a teenager 
after serving in the army air corps in world war i he returned 
to cosmetics and invented a kissproof lipstick he then worked as 
a freelance inventor and was a complete failure by age 30 when 
his appendix ruptured 
after six weeks in the hospital he decided to become a 
playwright he discarded his first play his second written in six 
days and called strictly dishonorable was a big hit on 
broadway and ran for 557 performances 
sturges went hollywood after writing 13 screenplays paramount 
studios let him direct his screenplay of the great mcginty 
which became the sleeper hit of 1940 and established him as 
hollywoods wonder boy 
it was an uneasy success for it threatened the studio system 
and made others in the industry jealous sturges as prodigal with 
his talent as his money made a string of great films and a string 
of bad ones 
he left paramount to work with howard hughes beginning the 
precipitous decline of his career by 1950 he was spent he died 
of a heart attack at the algonquin hotel in new york city on aug 
6 1959 
the sympathetic portrayal on american masters is a terrific 
introduction to sturges it is liberally intercut with clips from 
his greatest pictures and includes telling interviews with his 
friends and contemporaries 
the series has a promising lineup for the summer months next 
week american masters examines the career of actor and 
director john cassavetes on july 16 the series profiles director 
martin scorsese in addition to an extensive biography and 
interviews the scorsese profile looks at his new film good 
fellas the adaptation of nicholas pileggis wiseguy 
other masters profiles scheduled are composer cole porter 
newsman edward r murrow musician charlie parker record producer 
john hammond and author isaac bashevis singer 
