<TEXT>
many of the old scenes of summer kids with 
fireworks families huddled in cars at drivein movies the good 
humor man and his truck are fading from the american landscape 
but while summer is different now the lust for fun be it in a 
video arcade on or a hang glider is ever strong 
in the 1950s the status of your vacation was determined by 
how far you could drive and still survive says michael marsden 
a professor of american studies at bowling green state university 
in ohio now its how much you can pack into it people go away 
for vacation and come back exhausted 
americans jaded by a world where science fiction quickly 
becomes fact are starved for intense experiences that feed all 
their senses marsden says 
we just dont sit around on the front porch anymore he 
says were not interested in that were interested in living 
life 
as society becomes more frenetic summer might be the only time 
left for families to be together 
but dualincome families have less time summer or winter to 
spend together and households headed by single parents usually 
lack the funds and time to take even brief summer breaks 
the situation could worsen as recreation becomes more hightech 
and summer activities that once promoted togetherness disappear 
movies always have been an important summer ritual in america 
once carloads of families and amorous teenagers congregated 
almost religiously at driveins on humid summer nights 
now weeds grow over the driveins and moviegoers drive to chilly 
cinemas in shopping malls where they can choose from a dozen or 
more blockbusters 
fireworks the kind launched by dad at a july 4th picnic once 
exploded across the summer sky then were mostly extinguished by 
stringent federal bans 
now kids fire off explosions themselves albeit by computerized 
laser cannons on nearly lifelike video games 
even the good humor man and his ice cream truck melted away when 
the vendors in spiffy white uniforms were replaced by college 
students in tshirts and jeans 
there used to be a nostalgia with the trucks and the uniforms 
they were wellreceived by the community laments alice durocher 
