<TEXT>
blacks are winning historic nominations for 
key state offices as more experienced candidates enter the fray 
but few analysts expect them to make more than minimal gains in the 
november elections 
black candidates are a couple of election cycles away from 
winning a lot of things but one or two wins are within reach in 
1990 said democratic political consultant bob beckel 
one of the races being watched most closely is the north 
carolina senate race where black democrat harvey gantt is 
challenging republican sen jesse helms in another highprofile 
contest andrew young is vying for the democratic gubernatorial 
nomination in georgia 
currently the nation has one black governor no black senators 
and 24 black us house members 
most of the primary election victories for blacks have come in 
the south where the black population is the greatest the pattern 
there seems to be following that of virginias l douglas wilder 
who last year became the nations first black elected governor 
like wilder many in the current crop of black democratic 
candidates and nominees cut their political teeth in local office 
or government appointments wilder who had served in the state 
legislature ran and won as an incumbent lieutenant governor 
these are mostly black political leaders who were not in the 
civil rights movement who came into politics through elected 
offices starting at local city council and mayors and on up 
beckel said 
i just think its a process of finally coming into their 
own he said 
cheryl miller senior researcher at the joint center for 
political and economic studies a black thinktank doubts there 
will be any significant victories this year among the black 
statewide and primary runoff winners 
but she said the early primary votes signal the glass ceiling 
is not continuing to be an obstacle in the movement toward 
statewide candidacies by blacks and give encouragement to others 
who might consider running for statewide office 
in north carolina gantt the former twoterm mayor of 
charlotte defied conventional wisdom in last months runoff 
election and became the nations first black democratic senate 
nominee 
gantt faces a formidable opponent in seeking to unseat helms 
who raised 17 million in his 1984 race and already has sounded the 
financial alarm to his supporters 
but democratic leaders say helms is vulnerable and point to 
polls showing support for his reelection at just 28 percent to 33 
percent and early surveys showing gantt gaining on or leading helms 
we see north carolina as one of the best opportunities for a 
democrat in 1990 said democratic senatorial campaign committee 
spokeswoman anita dunn 
im a betting man and i think people who write off gantts 
chances in north carolina are wrong said beckel that race 
looks as difficult now as one doug wilders race looked about eight 
or nine months before the election 
democratic state sen theo mitchell won his primary and earlier 
this month became south carolinas first black gubernatorial 
nominee for a major party since reconstruction but he is 
considered a distant longshot in his general election campaign 
against popular gop gov carroll campbell 
opinions are divided on whether andrew young will emerge from a 
democratic primary and likely runoff to become the partys 
gubernatorial nominee in georgia 
young whose roots are in the civil rights movement of the 
1960s faces a strong challenge from lt gov zell miller and 
others in the july 17 primary young the former mayor of atlanta 
has angered some blacks by breaking ranks and refusing to join a 
lawsuit filed by blacks seeking to abolish runoff elections in the 
state 
additionally said pollster claiborne darden andy has not 
cemented a moderate to conservative image like wilder 
on the republican side kenneth muskie harris beat out a 
white supremacist to get the nod for the lieutenant governors spot 
on the gop ticket in arkansas it marks only the second time a 
black has been a majorparty nominee for a constitutional office in 
the state 
