<TEXT>
its been a long haul from a shotgun house on 
a tennessee cotton farm to the country club hills address of koko 
taylors new home 
born and raised in a long narrow cabin on a sharecroppers farm 
outside memphis taylor 61 moved last month into a new home in 
the posh chicago suburb of country club hills between addresses 
spans a lifetime of the blues 
the latest chapter includes the release in april of a new album 
jump for joy on alligator records and her appearance in wild 
at heart director david lynchs new black comedy which won the 
golden palm award as the best film at the 43rd cannes film festival 
they called up alligator and wanted a woman blues singer to 
sing two songs taylor said in a recent interview as she prepared 
to move from her south side bungalow 
and i went out there to los angeles to do the part and man 
i aint stopped grinning yet because i was so happy about it and 
im still happy about it i cant wait for the movie to come out 
because i think im going to be the first one at the theater first 
time i had ever been live in a real movie 
taylor filmed a scene in the movie in which she appears with a 
band in a nightclub where a fight breaks out she performs two 
pieces written by lynch and described by taylors manager and 
alligator president bruce iglauer as 
grotesquecabaretbluesinfluenced ballads 
neither taylor nor iglauer plan to make movies a new direction 
for a career that started with family jam sessions on homemade 
instruments in tennessee although iglauer said he would like to 
see taylor portray herself in a film performing the blues is the 
staple that keeps taylors life together 
the only thing i have in mind is to keep on doing what im 
doing and making people happy all over the world with my music is 
my dream and what i enjoy doing most taylor said 
that dream was nurtured in tennessee cotton fields 
i used to listen to the radio and when i was about 18 years 
old bb king was a disc jockey and he had a radio program 15 
minutes a day over in west memphis ark and he would play the 
blues and i would hear different records and things by muddy 
waters bessie smith memphis minnie sonnyboy williams and all 
these people you know which i just loved 
my oldest brother made himself a guitar by putting hay bailing 
wire tying it on a nail in the back of our little shotgun house 
and my little brother made hisself a harmonica out of a corn cob 
and of course i was the vocalist and we would all get together 
and jam and sing and play music and entertain ourselves she said 
also in the meantime my dad said everybody in the household 
had to go to church so every sunday i went to church and i grew 
up singing gospel i would sing in the church choir every sunday 
so what it amounted to was you know we would sing gospel on 
sunday and blues on monday 
taylor began adding the blues to the rest of her week after 
coming to chicago with richard pops taylor her husband of 35 
years who died last year they set up house on the south side home 
to a bustling music scene and cradle of the rawedged urban sound 
of chicago blues the roster of local bands playing in the 1950s 
and 60s in this clubland was a whos who of blues talent muddy 
waters howlin wolf elmore james buddy guy and others 
i started going to these local clubs me and my husband and 
everybody got to know us taylor said and then the guys would 
start letting me sit in you know come up on the bandstand and do 
a tune 
that was for fun the blues as a business began about 1963 when 
composer willie dixon working for chess records at the time heard 
her singing with howlin wolfs band 
he said you know you can really sing the blues he said 
i never heard a woman sing the blues like you sing the blues he 
said thats what the world needs today is more womens to sing the 
blues he said we got plenty men singing the blues but its 
more women 
taylors bestselling record to date was wang dang doodle 
written by dixon and recorded reluctantly by taylor in 1964 
i thought it was the silliest sounding song i had ever heard 
talk of she said acknowledging now that the records success 
got her career rolling 
it is still rolling along taylor still tours nine months a 
year doing mostly onenight stands she has recorded 12 albums 
and jump for joy her sixth for alligator is winning critical 
acclaim shes been nominated for a grammy award for seven of her 
last eight records and won for best blues recording in 1984 
the thing with koko is the combination of the talent as a 
musician and the talent as a performer because in blues you cant 
really separate them iglauer said and the third part of that 
is kokos professionalism and by that i dont just mean showing 
up on time i mean its her willingness to perform 
in addition to performing one of taylors other interests for 
the future is to return to the book she is writing to chronicle her 
life 
i dont know if the book will ever be published or not but if 
it dont ill just know i wrote it and ill enjoy doing it she 
said 
theres been a resurgence in the popularity of the blues and 
taylor is reaping the benefits 
i believe that the blues are going all the way to the top 
because right now blues is getting more recognition than it has 
ever gotten in the past and thats all it needs and thats all it 
takes because the blues never got the recognition she said 
</TEXT>
