<TEXT>
simon mahlathini delicately replaced the 
halfsmoked camel in its pack the growling singer of south 
africas township jive would save the cigarette until after the 
interview 
the gesture was indicative with worldwide acclaim coming to his 
group 26 years after its founding mahlathini still has the thrift 
born of life in south africas deprived black townships he and his 
three mahotella queens still cling to their identity as the musical 
heartandsoul of township music 
nothing has changed said mildred manxola the boisterous 
anchor of the trio that accompanies mahlathini white people are 
enjoying our music they dont understand the words but they hear 
the beat for us to see them dancing means they really 
understand it 
founded in 1964 the group fell on rough times in the 1970s 
while funk and disco flourished and broke up but they reunited in 
the early 80s and started traveling the world testing other 
styles finding new audiences and reigniting interest in 
mbaqanga a relentless dance music that blends traditional zulu 
rhythm and words street music and international pop 
the 53yearold mahlathini born simon nkabinde is called the 
lion of soweto for his raspy singing the queens manxola 
hilda tloubatia and nobesuthu shawe all in their mid40s are 
called mahotella for the many hotels theyve graced over the 
years the four are backed by their producers eclectic makgona 
tsohle band 
the group is now nearing the end of its second north american 
tour a 50city whirlwind in 2 months their first venture last 
year had a modest halfdozen stops 
im very excited that our music has been accepted said 
mahlathini a softspoken almost shy man who started performing 
at age 12 
even at home the music is getting bigger now they are 
going back to our roots in the life of south african music he 
said in an interview 
the music cooked up in the caged environment of south africas 
townships racially segregated cities where the majority black 
population lives has elements of reggae soul and even gospel in 
addition to african the driving bass lines joyous percussion and 
wailing saxophone join with the queens playful sometimes 
dissonant harmonizing to make an uplifting sound designed for 
dancing 
mahlathini quiet and reserved offstage becomes a spry 
performer onstage with his rumbling voice and staccato 
expressions all four clad in native zulu leopand skins and 
headdresses spice the music with nonstop choreographed dance 
steps 
but maintaining the style may be something of a challenge as 
they face western audiences the demand for incorporating western 
sounds into african music has increased since compatriots ladysmith 
black mambazo gained wide attention in the west on paul simons 
graceland album 
collaboration with the british group art of noise already has 
left a definite electronic mark on mahlathinis latest album 
parissoweto 
even producer west nkosi who helped refine mbaqanga in the 60s 
and discovered ladysmith black mambazo envisions using more 
western styles and pitches the practitioners of township jive as a 
doanything ensemble 
we will never say no to anybody who wants us to do something 
together because we want to show them we are a 
jackofalltrades that we can do anything said nkosi whose 
band name in zulu is translated the band that knows eveything 
mahlathinis 1987 parissoweto album distributed by 
celluloid in europe and polydor in the united states featured a 
redo of its trademark tune yebo with art of noises driving 
bass beat and electronically created yelps 
whatever the approach it hasnt overrun the groups native 
sound which is raking in wildly receptive audiences in japan 
australia europe and the united states 
we thought the americans would enjoy our music to our 
surprise we find that theyre going mad they wont let us go off 
the stage nkosi said in an interview this music is there to 
relieve anything that might have disturbed you mentally or in your 
heart you find that you are offending yourself if you listen to 
this music sitting down 
the group sees its music as psychological aid for its listeners 
much like it was in the townships during the worst of apartheid 
our people were unprivileged the only freedom they had was in 
this music nkosi said we design it to educate our children 
how to live with other people and whats happening presently to 
them and how to respect one another 
londonbased emi records produced mahlathinis first album of 
township music in 1952 then nkosi spotted him in 1964 playing 
weddings nkosi enlisted the queens in durban and produced the 
groups first album in 1964 under the whiteowned south african 
label gallo 
but getting the music out was and remains a problem he said 
blacks couldnt go into white stores to buy the albums and few 
black stores existed township radio stations were on the air only 
a few hours a week and white clubs were restricted forcing the 
group to find its audience personally 
we used to go to record stores and play in front and then 
give the record number to the audience nkosi said we went 
to the mines to find people coming from all over south africa 
nkosi split with gallo and later in 1987 took the group to 
europe where it recorded parissoweto featuring the delightful 
kazet and the raucous yebo 
but no matter where the popularity will take mahlathini and the 
mahotella queens the group will never forget where it came from 
from the very beginning it was for the people nkosi said 
it was for the struggle 
</TEXT>
