<TEXT>
jim abrams chief of the beijing bureau of the 
associated press is completing a fouryear assignment in china 
these are his reflections 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the drama of changing china has had touches of 
the heroic and the farcical too often it is haunted by tragedy 
it is a story that in the past four years indeed over the past 
40 has been marked by consistent themes 
the forces of change given center stage speak out and are 
suppressed the suppressors relax their vigilance and the 
adversaries rise again 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 1986 shao yanxiang a poet says it is the best period 
of literary creation in modern chinese history anyone can 
write the way he wants and the 100 flowers concept of free 
expression introduced by mao tsetung in 1956 has finally come 
true 
mao may have expressed the concept but those who took his 
advise and spoke out were persecuted 
maos successor deng xiaoping allowed a brief flirtation with 
free expression in the 1979 democracy wall movement some who bared 
their souls are still in prison 
in 1986 however the staterun movie industry awards prizes to 
the black cannon incident a scathing indictment of 
bureaucratic stupidity zhang xianliangs semiautobiographical 
novel half of man is woman shocks chinese readers with its 
frank look at political repression and sexual desire 
rambo superman and pavarotti play to overflow crowds chinese 
are cast as eunuchs and red guards in the film last emperor 
the door to the west appears firmly open 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january 1987 thousands of students demanding democratic reform 
trudge through the snowcovered midnight streets of beijing to 
tiananmen square asked if he is afraid of the police one replies 
we are students they would never hurt us 
the student movement constrained by harsh winter weather and 
lack of leadership is shortlived but the repercussions are 
serious 
hu yaobang dengs heir apparent is purged as communist party 
chief for his prostudent leanings a chilling campaign is launched 
against bourgeois liberalization or attraction to western 
ideas 
old socialist heroes are resurrected such as the late 
footsoldier lei feng a cartoonlike figure who devoted his life to 
doing good deeds and loving the party 
a new antihero astrophysicist fang lizhi is discovered and 
kicked out of the party for telling students to question their 
leaders 
sartre and lawrence are pulled off bookshelves and writers are 
told to write for the masses there has been nothing worth 
reading twice one said later in the year most writers are 
very cautious and keep their work on a very small scale 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
november 1987 proponents of reform triumph premier zhao 
ziyang who favors reform is named party chief at a national 
congress his mentor deng gives up most of his posts and forces 
aging conservatives to retire 
zhao asked about infighting between conservative and reform 
groups says the two factions have merged into one 
a star of the congress is guan guangmei a middleaged woman who 
took over eight moribund staterun food shops in a northern city 
and built a thriving business i will not be a capitalist she 
says but the state allows some people to get prosperous 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 1988 dengs marketoriented reforms appear entrenched 
china must push ahead with price reform the party newspaper 
partys peoples daily says to avoid rampant black markets 
heavier burdens of government subsidies and worsening of the social 
mood 
socialism is not a cake that can be ordered and there is no 
fixed pattern for socialism says social scientist li honglin in 
a year li will be imprisoned for making such statements 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
february 1989 president bush after meeting chinese leaders in 
beijing expresses confidence that when future generations of 
chinese and americans look back upon this time theyll say that 
the winds of change blew favorably upon our lands 
chinese leaders possibly distracted by growing economic 
problems and moves by conservative premier li peng to slow down 
reform evince a startling tolerance of political and artistic 
expression 
economists propose radical changes in the system intellectuals 
sign letters calling for the release of political prisoners and 
state television broadcasts a documentary questioning the very 
essence of chinese culture 
none of us knows how long this will last says 
selfdescribed free artist yang wei but its a good time to 
be creating 
an avantgarde art show preceded by an exhibit of nude 
paintings at beijings main museum features a waterbed filled with 
dead fish huge balloons shaped like breasts and a woman artist who 
shoots her own work with a bb gun 
tolerance has its limits police forcibly prevent fang lizhi 
from attending a banquet given by bush 
fang says of the government it is weak and it is frightened 
all i wanted to do was shake the hands of the president and mrs 
bush 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may 1989 an elderly woman blocks the path of a truck carrying 
soldiers ordered to end the prodemocracy demonstrations which had 
drawn crowds of up to 1 million 
she says to the soldiers the students are very weak how can 
you have the heart to suppress them beijing supports them if you 
advance it will be over my body 
two weeks later on june 3 the soldiers advance over the bodies 
of hundreds perhaps thousands of unarmed people deng praises the 
army for quelling a counterrevolutionary rebellion intended to 
overthrow the party and the socialist system 
thousands of political activists are imprisoned zhao is purged 
and accused of supporting student agitators millions of students 
and workers face long hours of political indoctrination hearing 
over and over again that without the communist party there would 
be no new china only socialism can save china 
lei feng the supermodel returns with a vengeance 
class struggle and imperialist threats are revived and 
according to official reports students rush to bookstores to buy 
the works of marx and lenin 
artists are told their works must be based on the idea of from 
the masses to the masses 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
october 1989 tiananmen square four months after the 
demonstrators were driven out is taken over by 100000 soldiers 
workers and students who dance and sing paeans on the 40th 
anniversary of communist party rule in china 
deng and other leaders watch from the rostrum of tiananmen gate 
as 30000 fireworks explode in the sky 
thousands of police and soldiers patrol nearby streets to keep 
uninvited guests away and prevent sabotage many are in riot gear 
carrying automatic rifles and electric prods 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 1990 thousands of armed police seal roads around beijing 
universities to prevent commemoration of the first anniversary of 
the military crackdown students powerless but defiant break 
bottles and hold a small campus demonstration 
millions of beijing residents peacefully spent this monday in 
busy work and pleasant rest the official xinhua news agency said 
tiananmen square still guarded by several thousand soldiers is 
closed to the public for four days leading up to the anniversary 
a beijing court citing the need to ensure social stability and 
severely attack criminal elements before the asian games in 
beijing in september orders the mass execution of 11 convicted 
criminals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
no one predicts when the current ideological spasm will give way 
to a new period in which ideas are encouraged rather than 
suppressed some say it may take the death of deng and a subsequent 
political crisis 
china has continued to change in both profound and humble ways 
in four years its 11 billion people have been introduced to 
stock markets bankruptcy contract labor private housing 
compulsory education through the 9th grade and opinion polls 
they have kentucky fried chicken off tiananmen square mickey 
mouse on television every sunday golf courses are built next to 
the ming tombs and hilton hotels rise in the hearts of ancient 
cities 
free markets run by 17 million private entrepreneurs continue 
to thrive 
beijing residents who once ate cabbage all winter now have 
cucumbers green peppers carrots and broccoli 
peasants are saving for tvs city people for video players and 
telephones 
the leaders in beijing can force people to study mao but they 
can no longer halt the national drive for richer and freer lives 
thats irreversible 
</TEXT>
