<TEXT>
sylvia fidgeted with an unlit cigarette 
telling how she has spent 35 of her 49 years firing heroin into 
her veins lately she said its been harder and harder to find 
decent quality heroin 
theres only manmade chemicals out there said sylvia 
which is not her real name tugging a robe closer to her thin 
frame if there were better stuff out there word would get 
around 
yet the drug enforcement administration says there is better 
stuff out there that bumper crops of opium overseas are flooding 
the united states with pure cheap heroin 
if thats so no one seems to know where the drug is going 
health care workers for example say the number of people who 
wound up in emergency rooms and morgues because of heroin actually 
decreased last year and officials at another federal drug control 
office say theres no evidence of a heroin epidemic 
its possible that emergency room doctors and medical examiners 
may not yet be seeing the effects of purer cheaper heroin 
another theory holds that because of the drugs increased 
purity people are getting high by smoking and snorting it those 
methods are less likely than injection to cause overdoses that 
require medical care so more people could be using the drug 
without coming to the attention of authorities 
a third possibility is that the influx of heroin could be 
overstated 
the dea doesnt think so the heroin situation is booming 
said felix jimenez who heads the agencys heroin desk its 
here its absolutely here 
his predecessor ed heath said the dea is not being alarmist 
it just wants to be prepared we dont want to play catchup like 
we did with cocaine 
but david tell deputy chief of staff of the office of national 
drug control policy said such warnings are an exaggerated 
gloomanddoom prediction 
is more heroin coming into the country maybe said tell 
are more people using that heroin i would guess quite the 
opposite 
sylvia for one has given up her search for better heroin she 
recently entered the detoxification program at the francis scott 
key medical center part of the johns hopkins health system here 
if heroin on the streets is now more pure one might expect more 
addicts to accidentally overdose landing in the emergency room or 
the morgue 
however the number of heroin users who died or who required 
emergency room treatment last year leveled off in most us cities 
and even decreased in some thats according to figures compiled by 
the governments drug abuse warning network which had tracked 
steady increases during the 1980s 
only two of the 21 cities surveyed regarding emergency room 
visits bucked the downward trend the number nearly doubled in san 
francisco and increased 10 percent in baltimore 
even in new york city which has the nations largest 
concentration of heroin addicts the number of heroinrelated 
emergency room visits declined the last two years 
the number of heroinrelated deaths fell in many cities 
including boston detroit new york philadelphia and washington 
dc but the preliminary report from a panel of medical examiners 
found some startling exceptions in chicago the number of 
heroinrelated deaths skyrocketed 655 percent from 1987 to last 
year in san diego the number rose 77 percent 
another way to track new drug trends is by monitoring people 
whove been arrested but tests of arrestees nationwide found no 
noticeable change in heroin use from 1988 to the fall of 1989 
according to justice department drug use forecasting studies 
no one knows exactly how many people use heroin in the united 
states the 1982 official estimate of 500000 heroin addicts has 
never been updated 
a 1988 household survey of drug use found 19 million americans 
aged 12 and older said they had used heroin at least once said 
mona brown spokeswoman for the national institute on drug abuse 
which conducted the survey but that number is considered 
conservative because the survey does not cover the homeless or 
people in jail 
its unclear whether there are lots of new users 
dr don c des jarlais director of chemical dependency research 
at beth israel hospital in new york said heroin today is mostly 
used by people who have used in the past 
heroin users calling the washington area council on alcoholism 
and drug abuse hot line are 28 years old and older said 
epidemiologist dr michael stoil of the council that tells me it 
is not being picked up heavily among the youth 
the dea is concerned that street heroins high potency could 
attract new users who can get high just by smoking or snorting it 
without using dangerous intravenous needles 
about 75 percent to 80 percent of heroin users at francis scott 
keys adolescent detoxification unit smoke the drug said dr 
archie golden who runs the program fifteen percent snort it and a 
few inject it 
many are likely to turn to needles eventually warned diana 
potter a nurse with the adult unit 
sometimes the kids come in and theyll say oh im never 
going to use a needle you know potter said with a knowing 
laugh we tell them a little bit down the road you keep this 
up you will be using a needle 
the dea cites several reasons for arguing that there is an 
influx of heroin studies show global opium production is on the 
rise and even though the amount of heroin seized by federal 
agencies is increasing the street price is going down 
the state departments international narcotics control strategy 
report estimates worldwide opium production this year will total as 
much as 4734 metric tons about double the 1986 estimate 
dea tests of street samples in a halfdozen cities found that 
the cost per milligram of pure heroin dropped from 301 in 1988 to 
179 last year average purity increased from 236 percent to 252 
percent compared with single digits a decade ago 
though the amount of heroin confiscated can fluctuate from year 
to year the trend recently has been toward much larger seizures 
from 1982 through 1987 the dea and customs service each 
confiscated 200 to 440 kilograms of heroin a year since 1988 the 
annual seizures have ranged from 279 to 829 kilos 
but even huge seizures didnt cause a ripple in the market 
heath said case activity is going up jimenez said 
quantities are going up in every seizure 
he rejected the notion that drug agents may simply be doing a 
better job 
this means more heroin is coming into the country jimenez 
said 
dr donald jasinsky who runs francis scott keys adult 
detoxification program suggested that there simply may be a lag 
between the influx of heroin and hospital and morgue cases 
you may have to have drug users using for awhile before 
you see an increase in public health and social problems 
jasinsky said 
