<TEXT>
verbal sniping between the federal agencies 
that oversee the securities and futures markets is heating up again 
commodity futures trading commission chairman wendy gramm says a 
study by the rival securities and exchange commission on last 
octobers 190point stock market plunge is misleading and 
imprecise 
sec chairman richard c breeden says the cftcs study of the 
1989 market minicrash had significant methodological defects 
he also likened it to saying except for the period of time 
between 7 am and noon pearl harbor day was a good day 
we stand by our report and every word in it breeden told a 
small group of reporters thursday 
his sharp comments came in response to a letter gramm sent to 
the chairman of a house subcommittee that oversees the cftc 
both the sec which regulates stocks bonds and the exchanges 
that trade them and the cftc which oversees the futures markets 
have been locked in a war of words over which agency has 
jurisdiction over financial products that share aspects of both 
securities and futures contracts 
the bush administration is pushing legislation that would strip 
the cftc of authority over stock index futures and give it to the 
sec 
in the wake of a 190point plunge in the dow jones industrial 
average a key market indicator last fall both regulatory 
agencies studied the causes of the trading slide which occurred 
shortly after ual corp announced financing for a managementled 
leveraged buyout had fallen through 
last month both agencies released their reports the cftc 
concluded that index arbitrage a computerized program trading 
strategy blamed by many for exacerbating the 1987 stock market 
crash was not a major factor in the stock slide 
it also found no evidence of stock index futures market 
manipulation 
stock index futures often used in program trading strategies by 
large institutional investors like pension funds let investors 
trade on the movement of a basket of stocks without having to buy 
the underlying stocks 
the sec and other critics of index arbitrage claim it causes 
wild price swings or volatility index arbitragers try to take 
advantage of small price differences between the stock and futures 
markets by simultaneously buying large orders in one market while 
selling in the other 
the sec study released last month found that index arbitrage and 
other program trading strategies accelerated the 69 percent market 
drop an unusually high percentage of volume during the 90minute 
slide was conducted through computerprogram trading the sec study 
concluded 
rep glenn english dokla chairman of the panel that oversees 
the cftc asked gramm to explain the discrepencies between the sec 
and cftc reports 
in a ninepage letter to english gramm said the two reports 
agree on most of the facts the secs report is misleading because 
it leaves some critical information out of its analysis 
the most obvious case is their emphasis on sell volume and 
only perfunctory mention of contemporaneous buy volume by the same 
trader groups gramm said 
breeden however insisted the sec report was more accurate 
because it focuses on the days trading after the ual announcement 
also breeden said the sec report looks at the pattern of net 
activities both buying and selling 
the cftc report chose to analyze the level of index arbitrage 
averaged over the entire day thats a little bit like saying that 
except for the period of time between 7 am and noon pear harbor 
day was a good day and on average there werent many problems 
breeden continued there was a specific event it began at a 
specific point in time and to try and disguise the developments 
that occurred during that period of time by averaging them in over 
a period of time that is totally irrelevent demonstrates the 
significant methodological defects of the cftc report 
</TEXT>
