designed to reduce the risk of engine fires 
gm discontinued the fiero in 1988 
the automaker told the national highway traffic safety 
administration in december it would recall the plasticbodied 
midengined cars because of engine fire problems the automaker 
said thursday it will begin notifying owners next month 
notification will be sent in july to owners of 1984 
fourcylinder models in august to owners of 198588 six cylinder 
models in september to owners of 198586 fourcylinder models and 
in october to owners of 198788 fourcylinder models pontiac said 
the company said the repairs would be performed free of charge 
the 308000 cars are the number believed still registered 
pontiac spokesman reg harris said the company built 328000 fieros 
from their introduction in july 1983 as a 1984 model to their 
demise at the end of the 1988 model year 
harris said 1451 fires have been reported in the cars 100 
involving minor injuries 
dealers will make changes to prevent oil or other engine fluids 
from spilling on hot exhaust system parts also fourcylinder cars 
made in 198486 will have new exhaust manifolds installed similar 
to manifolds made standard on later models 
the company urged owners to carefully monitor oil levels in the 
meantime as described in owners manuals of sixcylinder models 
and in special booklets mailed last fall to owners of fourcylinder 
models 
owners should have the cars checked immediately if they notice 
overheating vibration or power loss harris said 
in 1987 gm recalled 125000 fourcylinder fieros produced in 
the 1984 model year for alterations that included boosting oil 
capacity to four quarts from three the company also urged owners 
to check the engine oil every time they bought gas 
</TEXT>
