<TEXT>
congress is considering a resolution that would 
direct the federal reserve to reduce inflation gradually to zero 
but says a critic there is a major defect in the effort 
the defect says richard w rahn is that the resolution would 
so to speak appoint the fox to guard the chicken coop the federal 
reserve he says is the cause of inflation not its cure 
rahn doesnt equivocate to him the issue is clear the 
central bank and only the central bank causes inflation and as 
you probably know the fed is the central bank of the united states 
you might perceive something convoluted in such thinking but 
oddly says critic rahn the convoluted thinking is the 
conventional thinking 
the whole notion that the central bank should be the economys 
designated inflation fighter has the world upside down says 
rahn whose professional position might suggest he is a defender 
rather than critic of convention 
rahn is vice president and chief economist of the us chamber 
of commerce 
in testimony on house joint resolution 409 to establish price 
stability as a national objective rahn instructed congress that 
the nation has a fiat money system controlled by government and 
outside the control of the rule of law 
government he said retains a monopoly over money by spending 
it and then forcing the fed to accommodate the spending by 
manipulating the money supply and attempting to keep it from 
inflating the market economy 
i believe that as long as the government maintains a monopoly 
over money and relies on an unaccountable government central bank 
to manage that monopoly inflation will persist he told members 
of congress 
in seeking to accommodate that government spending he said the 
fed whipsaws the economy between inflation and recession rather 
than pursuing a longterm policy consistent with stable economic 
growth 
sustained inflation is always a monetary phenomenon and 
trends in the real economy when divorced from changes in monetary 
growth have little bearing on past present and future 
inflation he said 
in short if government kept spending in check and if the fed 
didnt feel compelled to accomodate that spending thered be no 
inflation 
you could detect additional outrage in rahns testimony fed 
board members he remarked are political appointees who once 
appointed are left unaccountable for their decisions when they 
testify before congress he said they are sometimes purposely 
vague even given to misinformation 
in economics statistics speak the wholesale price index rahn 
said stayed generally level from 1795 to 1913 then what happened 
in that year the federal reserve was established 
from then until 1951 when the fed became fully independent the 
rate doubled by last year said rahn the rate had increased 
ninefold from 1913 
the fact of the matter said rahn is that monetary policy 
call it fed policy cannot offset finetune counterbalance or 
reserve the adverse economic effects of improper fiscal and 
regulatory policy 
if congress spends and borrows too much the economy must pay 
the price in underinvestment reduced output and increased 
unemployment he said fed policy he said can do nothing to 
shelter the economy 
when the fed seeks to counteract these policy mistakes he said 
it merely exacerbates the consequences 
inflation will be the direct result and then ultimately a 
recession will be induced as the fed further reacts to the 
inflation it created by its original attempt to offset bad policy 
rahn would establish a monetary rule to limit fed discretion and 
govern monetary policy require that fed policy be set and 
implemented in public not behind closed doors and limit its 
authority in foreign currency markets 
moreover so that monetary policy wouldnt gyrate to accommodate 
government overspending he would commit congress to restrain 
spending to no more than the inflation rate 
</TEXT>
