<DOCNO> AP900629-0259 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it was too hot and dry to grow corn and 
soybeans in 1988 so farmers charles kerchenfaut and rob read 
decided to raise shrimp on the prairie 
more than 3000 freshwater shrimp now comb the bottom of a 
1000gallon tank to forage for commercial feed or hide from their 
cannibalistic cousins in a homemade shrimp condo structure 
its just a research project right now said kerchenfaut 
weve got to learn it before we can make a profit 
but two who are longtime friends and neighbors have harvested 
about 300 shrimp up to six inches long and sold them to pet shops 
for use in aquariums the shrimp sell for 5 to 7 each retail but 
the men declined to say how much they receive wholesale 
if we get the volume it would be nice eventually to supply 
the food market most shrimp now come from overseas said read 
we could hit the organic market these shrimp are 100 percent 
pure raised in water without any toxins 
the men said they got into shrimp production out of curiosity 
and because they had little else to do during the 1988 drought 
read raises grain on 2800 acres with his brother kerchenfaut 
farms 1200 acres 
the green plastic tank where the shrimp are raised is inside an 
old garage on kerchenfauts farm in ford county in eastcentral 
illinois 
water is filtered continuously to remove waste temperature and 
oxygen levels are monitored feed is added twice daily water 
quality is tested daily 
the farming begins when weekold shrimp are shipped in plastic 
bags from suppliers in places like puerto rico and hawaii 
theyre small said read pull out an eyelash thats 
what theyd be like 
they do not grow at the same rate but in three to four months 
many have reached market size several inches in length 
one of the biggest challenges the men faced was the lack of 
information about raising freshwater shrimp in tanks they read 
everything they could find about shrimp and called other producers 
and researchers 
we spent about 1000 on equipment said read the phone 
bills were probably our biggest expense 
read visited scientists at southern illinois university where 
chris kohler is conducting research at the fisheries research 
laboratory to develop better feed and better ways for producers to 
raise shrimp 
just about all the shrimp you eat are marine salt water 
shrimp kohler said the freshwater shrimp often are called 
prawn i think they are quite tasty and they bring a premium 
price 
the farmers learned that shrimp are cannibalistic hence 
adequate commercial feed and the condos for vulnerable molting 
shrimp to hide from the others 
they also learned that temperatures below 62 degrees are fatal 
to shrimp so when electricity was lost during the february ice 
storm a generator was used to heat the shrimp building 
the house was cold but the shrimp were warm kerchenfaut 
chuckled 
neither man has sampled the shrimp but read says he plans to 
get one pretty quick they are considering a summer cookout for 
neighbors featuring homegrown sweet corn and shrimp 
a lot of our neighbors are curious about what were doing 
said read i suppose some of them just think were nuts 
not the local chapter of future farmers of america adviser 
richard long who teaches at ford central high school said about 
35 ffa members will raise freshwater shrimp next fall kerchenfaut 
and read will share their experiences 
</TEXT>
