consumer confidence declined significantly in 
june according to a monthly survey conducted by the conference 
board the business group said thursday 
the group said its consumer confidence index for june stood at 
1025 percent down almost five points from may the year 1985 
represents 100 in the index which is based on survey responses 
the drop in confidence primarily reflects increasing concern 
about jobs said fabian linden executive director of the 
conference boards consumer research center 
over the past three months a growing number of people have 
reported that jobs are hard to get and there has been rising 
uneasiness about job opportunities in the immediate future 
linden said in a statement 
fewer than 24 percent of the survey participants reported that 
jobs were plentiful a 3 percentage point loss from may in 
addition those who fear there will be fewer jobs over the next six 
months outnumber those who expect more jobs continuing a pattern 
of the past few months linden said 
still while the measure of consumer confidence is now lower 
than it has been in more than 2 years there are no indications of 
impending recession linden said 
the boards survey of 5000 us households is conducted by 
national family opinion inc of toledo ohio the survey has a 
margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points 
