<TEXT>
federal securities regulators said thursday 
that a linkage system for the longdelayed multiple listing of 
options could be up and running by the end of the year 
securities and exchange commission chairman richard c breeden 
said four of the nations five options exchanges have reached 
agreement on a system for linking the various trading marketplaces 
breeden and sec market regulation division director richard g 
ketchum said however that the proposed system would have to go 
through the timeconsuming sec approval process before it could 
begin operation 
its not a long period i think we could still be looking at a 
linkage system being up by the end of 1990 or early 1991 of the 
type agreed to by the four exchanges said ketchum 
neither official would say what action the sec will take later 
this month when a voluntary delay in multiple listings ends 
we would have to reserve official judgement until we see a 
filing for a linkage system by the exchanges said breeden 
he said only the philadelphia stock exchange has not agreed to 
the proposed linkage system 
since january at sec request the nations options exchanges 
have delayed their phasein of multiple listings for options 
already being traded until june 30 that was to allow extra time to 
come up with a linkage system 
we wanted to take the time from january until june 30 to have 
an intensive review of whether a linkage system is feasible said 
breeden in an interview in his sixth floor office we have 
concluded that it is unquestionably feasible we have a specific 
system that four of the exchanges have agreed is a good one and 
should be built the next step now would be moving toward 
implementation of a system he added 
an option contract is the right to buy or sell a certain 
security at a specified price for a set period of time options are 
traded on stocks listed on exchanges or traded overthecounter via 
computer 
until earlier this year most options on the stocks listed on an 
exchange could be traded only in one marketplace at a time the 
privlege for trading a specific option assigned by lottery is not 
permitted on any other exchange 
but a rule passed by the sec last year abolished the limitations 
on multiple trading of options all new options listed for trading 
after january can be traded on any options exchange 
but breeden asked the heads of the american stock exchange the 
chicago board of options exchange the new york stock exchange the 
pacific stock exchange and the philadelphia exchange to 
voluntarilly refrain from multiple listing of existing options 
until june 30 
