<TEXT>
a jury friday awarded 159 million to an inventor 
who claimed gte products corp pulled the plug on his fledgling 
lighting business by stealing his idea for a cool lamp used in 
movie studios 
a us district court jury agreed with george panagiotou a 
former rock band manager turned lighting entrepreneur who said he 
got the idea for his socalled cool light during his years as a 
boston nightclub manager in the early 1970s 
panagiotou had charged that trade secrets for his cool light 
were unfairly appropriated by the danvers massbased lighting 
giant which then manufactured a similar product and sent 
panagiotous own company into ruin 
the jury found that panagiotous invention of a reflector that 
cut the heat from movie lights was a trade secret improperly 
obtained by gte a division of gte corp of stamford conn and 
that gte officials falsely told panagiotou they could make the 
reflectors needed for the lamp 
but the jury also found that gte did not use the secret to 
advance its own business interests and did not profit from 
panagiotous cool light secret 
edwin mccabe panagiotous lawyer said the award would come to 
about 25 million with interest 
panagiotou who has since started a successful home video light 
company in los angeles said he was elated by the verdict 
i feel fantastic i feel great because its over its behind 
us he said we certainly triumphed 
vincent dalessandro a gte spokesman said the firm would 
appeal 
were disappointed by the verdict dalessandro said our 
contention is that weve done nothing wrong there was no secret 
we didnt break a contract and we contend there should be no 
damages 
panagiotou born in romania of greek descent came to boston at 
age 16 started working in the citys nightclubs and eventually 
helped form the rock band aerosmith and managed such groups as rush 
he said in court records that he started developing the cool 
light when he realized how uncomfortable performers were under the 
wilting heat of the performance lights of the 1970s 
cool light was used in the production of tv programs popular in 
the late 1970s and early 1980s including lou grant police 
woman switch and little house on the prairie 
panagiotou filed the suit in california in 1984 the trial began 
last month and attracted such stars as ed asner and michael landon 
to testify on panagiotous behalf 
according to court documents celebrities such as robert wagner 
refused to act without cool lights once they had used them 
lawyers for cool light panagiotous firm argued that 
panagiotou was tricked into a gentlemans agreement with gte 
under the pact panagiotou would give gte his production 
secrets gte would manufacture a special reflector for the lights 
panagiotou would place the reflector in the light fixtures at his 
expense at his own plant and then distribute it to customers 
but soon after he revealed the unpatented secret gte 
discontinued the outside contracting of products made with some 
materials including those used for the reflector gte stopped 
supplying cool light with reflectors mccabe said 
cool light consequently folded while gte started distributing 
products made with the secret mccabe said 
gte had maintained that panagiotou failed to show there had been 
any trade secrets or that there had been a breach of contract 
since panagiotous company shut down other types of lights have 
been used in hollywood mccabe said 
but panagiotou said he planned to once again make the cool light 
were certain we will produce the cool light again he said 
no one has filled that gap in the market this time they will be 
improved 
</TEXT>
