interest greenstein said 
the irs started investigating arco in the mid1980s after rival 
oil companies complained its internal pricing policies were 
unjustifiably minimizing its taxes allowing it to charge less for 
gasoline than rivals in the competitive california retail market 
arco denied the allegations 
the dispute settled friday centered on the value assigned by 
arco to crude oil it pumped from north slope wells the irs 
contends arco assigned the oil a value lower than it should have at 
that point lessening the windfall profits tax which is based on a 
benchmark price derived from past production on a given oil field 
that lower windfall profits tax let arco ultimately set prices 
lower on the retail gasoline it sold at the pumps other oil 
companies complained 
the settlement was the latest in a series of similar cases 
dating back to the mid1980s for arco and other oil companies 
in 1986 for example arco agreed to pay the state of alaska 
243 million as part of a tax settlement covering the companys 
production on the north slope and cook inlet fields still 
unresolved from that time is a dispute with alaska over royalties 
paid on the same production alaska is demanding 320 million in 
that case greenstein said 
also that year arco agreed to pay 315 million in restitution 
and fines to settle allegations of violating federal oil price 
controls in the 1970s and early 1980s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

